betray him,
but I have to correct him

01:02:01.192 --> 01:02:02.565
because he says
"revealed,"

01:02:02.565 --> 01:02:03.480
that's what he means.
 

01:02:03.480 --> 01:02:07.849
The eternal love revealed
itself a new love.

01:02:07.849 --> 01:02:13.525
He is missing the whole sexual
language which is exactly the

01:02:13.525 --> 01:02:15.449
reason, thank you.
 

01:02:15.449 --> 01:02:20.068
That's exactly the reason why I
think that Francesca too can

01:02:20.068 --> 01:02:23.750
arguably be saved,
that's exactly the reason.

01:02:23.750 --> 01:02:28.329
The term he uses is
aperse,

01:02:28.329 --> 01:02:31.038
from the Italian,
in Italian we call it

01:02:31.038 --> 01:02:34.514
aprire,
very close to in English we

01:02:34.514 --> 01:02:39.423
have the word April,
by the way, as an opening of

01:02:39.423 --> 01:02:40.300
spring.
 

01:02:40.300 --> 01:02:42.760
Just to give you a sense of
etymology,

01:02:42.760 --> 01:02:49.416
it comes from aperire
Latin which really means to

01:02:49.416 --> 01:02:53.268
generate,
to bring to light,

01:02:53.268 --> 01:02:59.268
as a woman brings a birth to
light and life.

01:02:59.268 --> 01:03:02.186
That's really the word,
that's the meaning of the word,

01:03:02.186 --> 01:03:04.940
so it's as sexual and as
productive as it can be.

01:03:04.940 --> 01:03:08.385
Before I go back though to your
question about how is Dante

01:03:08.385 --> 01:03:11.679
going to--
what Dante is saying is that

01:03:11.679 --> 01:03:16.134
creation is the sexual process,
the sexual experience,

01:03:16.134 --> 01:03:18.900
which is exactly what Francesca
also did,

01:03:18.900 --> 01:03:21.980
breaking the law undoubtedly.
 

01:03:21.980 --> 01:03:24.969
She is in hell,
is she going to be in hell?

01:03:24.969 --> 01:03:28.440
Are we going to understand that
there is a possible continuity

01:03:28.440 --> 01:03:31.684
between what she did in a
physical sense and what Dante is

01:03:31.684 --> 01:03:33.449
doing in a spiritual sense?
 

01:03:33.449 --> 01:03:37.673
This is the whole point of the
discussion on cosmology and

01:03:37.673 --> 01:03:38.489
creation.
 

01:03:38.489 --> 01:03:41.184
That there is some kind of
continuity between the two

01:03:41.184 --> 01:03:43.480
modes;
not quite the same thing;

01:03:43.480 --> 01:03:46.579
of course, creation is a
different order of experience.

01:03:46.579 --> 01:03:50.655
There is a very thin line,
it's like a little breath

01:03:50.655 --> 01:03:55.452
of--breath that Francesca can
release at sea--or Beatrice who

01:03:55.452 --> 01:03:57.849
goes on talking endlessly.
 

01:03:57.849 --> 01:04:01.639
She too, that's the difference
between the two,

01:04:01.639 --> 01:04:03.679
so between the language of
sexuality,

01:04:03.679 --> 01:04:05.800
of physicality in
Inferno,

01:04:05.800 --> 01:04:08.387
and the language of
spirituality here in

01:04:08.387 --> 01:04:11.505
Paradise,
the line that is continuing

01:04:11.505 --> 01:04:15.146
between them and there is a
little difference but there is

01:04:15.146 --> 01:04:17.639
also a possibility of a
continuity,

01:04:17.639 --> 01:04:22.672
that's really exactly the
argument that I would make about

01:04:22.672 --> 01:04:23.289
that.
 

01:04:23.289 --> 01:04:27.882
Let me though tell you more,
in a historical way,

01:04:27.882 --> 01:04:32.858
so that if you don't agree with
what I said so be it,

01:04:32.858 --> 01:04:34.389
don't worry.
 

01:04:34.389 --> 01:04:39.413
I don't agree with it
completely on my own but I think

01:04:39.413 --> 01:04:44.246
that this--that's a radical
reading of the notion of

01:04:44.246 --> 01:04:47.659
cosmology and creation in Dante.
 

01:04:47.659 --> 01:04:50.219
Let me tell you something else
historically.

01:04:50.219 --> 01:04:54.268
Where is Dante taking these
ideas from?

01:04:54.268 --> 01:04:58.300
Whenever you read commentaries
on Dante,

01:04:58.300 --> 01:05:02.259
and I hope that some of you
will go on reading and reading

01:05:02.259 --> 01:05:05.721
also scholars,
thank you, critics--I see that

01:05:05.721 --> 01:05:10.510
nodding is just--
my heart it just gladdens when

01:05:10.510 --> 01:05:11.880
I see that.
 

01:05:11.880 --> 01:05:15.465
They all tell you--and I
indicated that too that Dante is

01:05:15.465 --> 01:05:19.820
some kind of an Aristotelian and
I was talking about metaphysics,

01:05:19.820 --> 01:05:23.739
how Aristotle calls it first
philosophy,

01:05:23.739 --> 01:05:25.280
Aristotelian terms.
 

01:05:25.280 --> 01:05:30.070
They never tell you where the
actual sources of Dante are.

01:05:30.070 --> 01:05:36.355
The sources of Dante about
cosmology and cosmography are

01:05:36.355 --> 01:05:38.869
really neo-platonic.
 

01:05:38.869 --> 01:05:43.920
The idea of creation,
especially one text that I have

01:05:43.920 --> 01:05:47.197
to mention,
this guy who writes the

01:05:47.197 --> 01:05:51.782
Cosmographia called a
twelfth-century man Bernard

01:05:51.782 --> 01:05:54.882
Sylvester,
a Frenchman,

01:05:54.882 --> 01:06:03.099
Bernard Sylvester who writes
Cosmographia,

01:06:03.099 --> 01:06:08.429
twelfth century known as the
author of School of Chartres.

01:06:08.429 --> 01:06:11.780
By the way this text were
available to Dante,

01:06:11.780 --> 01:06:16.809
we have a text of this man,
Cosmographia,

01:06:16.809 --> 01:06:19.018
one copy only because a
Florentine,

01:06:19.018 --> 01:06:23.480
later--he had it in Florence,
by the name of Boccaccio,

01:06:23.480 --> 01:06:26.344
some of you know very well,
he copied it down and

01:06:26.344 --> 01:06:27.539
transmitted to us.
 

01:06:27.539 --> 01:06:31.150
We know his handwriting because
we have his texts so we know,

01:06:31.150 --> 01:06:35.940
this is 1340,
Dante of course wrote about

01:06:35.940 --> 01:06:38.125
1302,
but clearly that text was

01:06:38.125 --> 01:06:38.909
available then.
 

01:06:38.909 --> 01:06:42.163
In this text,
Bernard gives an idea of

01:06:42.163 --> 01:06:46.559
creation and cosmological ideas,
physical ideas.

01:06:46.559 --> 01:06:49.306
They had been reading the
Timaeus in France and

01:06:49.306 --> 01:06:51.949
they were always surprised and
wondering what is the

01:06:51.949 --> 01:06:54.949
difference,
how can we go on having Plato

01:06:54.949 --> 01:06:59.739
say one thing about creation and
Genesis saying something else?

01:06:59.739 --> 01:07:04.360
How are we going to connect
these two forms,

01:07:04.360 --> 01:07:09.409
these two sources of tradition
and authority?

01:07:09.409 --> 01:07:16.291
They argue, he goes on talking
about the idea of a pre-existing

01:07:16.291 --> 01:07:18.289
world of matter.
 

01:07:18.289 --> 01:07:24.125
The natural world and a
malignant materiality and how

01:07:24.125 --> 01:07:29.960
this malignant materiality is
subdued into shape,

01:07:29.960 --> 01:07:34.929
and the subduing into shape is
always sexual language.

01:07:34.929 --> 01:07:38.579
Matura is that which
produces,

01:07:38.579 --> 01:07:43.289
generates, this is the text
that I believe stands behind

01:07:43.289 --> 01:07:48.768
Dante's physical explanation of
a universe which is physical,

01:07:48.768 --> 01:07:52.289
but at the same time it is not
just physical.

01:07:52.289 --> 01:07:56.199
It is also a theory of creation
and it's the theory of creation

01:07:56.199 --> 01:07:58.659
that has unpredictable
possibilities.

01:07:58.659 --> 01:08:01.250
This tells you that things can
be renewed.

01:08:01.250 --> 01:08:04.362
If you stay within the
bound--you see how he criticizes

01:08:04.362 --> 01:08:06.610
the physical conception of the
world.

01:08:06.610 --> 01:08:09.454
If you stay within those
boundaries you can't expect

01:08:09.454 --> 01:08:11.909
anything other than what you
already have.

01:08:11.909 --> 01:08:15.405
You cannot expect anymore evil
or any less evil than what you

01:08:15.405 --> 01:08:16.630
already experience.
 

01:08:16.630 --> 01:08:20.149
The only idea,
the way in which human beings

01:08:20.149 --> 01:08:24.856
can think about renewal,
can think about change or

01:08:24.856 --> 01:08:30.850
freedom, or origins is only
within the context of creation.

01:08:30.850 --> 01:08:34.680
That's exactly Dante's argument
and that's the profound

01:08:34.680 --> 01:08:38.440
justification for the
distinction between one order of

01:08:38.440 --> 01:08:42.060
experience and a different order
of experience.

01:08:42.060 --> 01:08:45.640
But if this is true,
and it is true for Dante,

01:08:45.640 --> 01:08:49.210
then I have to take also
seriously this idea of--

01:08:49.210 --> 01:08:52.873
this central event of
redemption, which now we

01:08:52.873 --> 01:08:57.189
understand what he takes that to
mean: the moment,

01:08:57.189 --> 01:08:59.788
the experience of the
incarnation.

01:08:59.788 --> 01:09:03.698
This is exactly--it follows--if
he has to--

01:09:03.698 --> 01:09:05.859
if he believes that there is
such a thing as--

01:09:05.859 --> 01:09:09.194
and he does--creation then he
has to believe that there is

01:09:09.194 --> 01:09:13.328
also the idea of recreation,
a second creation because the

01:09:13.328 --> 01:09:18.130
first creation clearly didn't
work out all that well so there

01:09:18.130 --> 01:09:20.449
is this other possibility.
 

01:09:24.720 --> 01:09:27.538
Please.
 

01:09:27.538 --> 01:09:31.390
Student:  I have the
sense that in these lines at the

01:09:31.390 --> 01:09:34.720
beginning of XXIX that we've
been talking about,

01:09:34.720 --> 01:09:40.911
that Dante is very aware of
being on theological thin ice or

01:09:40.911 --> 01:09:44.689
skating close to the danger
line,

01:09:44.689 --> 01:09:53.626
but the idea is the divine love
spills over out into a created

01:09:53.626 --> 01:09:59.779
world so that it can be
reflected back,

01:09:59.779 --> 01:10:05.135
endured, and loved in return in
the way that Paolo and Francesca

01:10:05.135 --> 01:10:06.750
loved each other.
 

01:10:06.750 --> 01:10:14.341
That's not far from the thought
that before creation God has

01:10:14.341 --> 01:10:22.447
everything but is still a little
lonely and that suggests a kind

01:10:22.447 --> 01:10:27.127
of imperfection,
or at least incompleteness,

01:10:27.127 --> 01:10:29.399
but how can God be incomplete?
 

01:10:29.399 --> 01:10:36.609
Dante begins this passage by
saying, not to acquire new

01:10:36.609 --> 01:10:39.896
goodness for himself;
this is the

01:10:39.896 --> 01:10:40.409
&gt;
 

01:10:40.409 --> 01:10:41.880
translation, which cannot be.
 

01:10:41.880 --> 01:10:43.118
Prof: That's perfect.
 

01:10:43.118 --> 01:10:49.720
Student:  That he wants
to announce before he offers his

01:10:49.720 --> 01:10:55.895
neo-platonic vision of the
relationship of--that God had to

01:10:55.895 --> 01:10:57.279
creation.
 

01:10:57.279 --> 01:11:03.033
He wants to signal his
orthodoxy to doubters who might

01:11:03.033 --> 01:11:09.548
hear in this something which is
less than perfectly Christian

01:11:09.548 --> 01:11:16.171
because it comes close to the
idea of a needy God or a God who

01:11:16.171 --> 01:11:21.710
in the way that every lover
needs something,

01:11:21.710 --> 01:11:26.140
and other to love in return,
is in a predicament and

01:11:26.140 --> 01:11:31.092
creation is the solution to the
predicament that God is in

01:11:31.092 --> 01:11:33.698
before the world was made.
 

01:11:33.698 --> 01:11:38.551
Prof: Okay,
the question is that--well,

01:11:38.551 --> 01:11:44.590
the question is more of a
comment by the maestro here.

01:11:44.590 --> 01:11:49.667
The comment is that Dante at
the beginning of Canto XXIX

01:11:49.667 --> 01:11:53.359
seems to be on a theologically
risky,

01:11:53.359 --> 01:11:56.305
on thin ice,
I am quoting,

01:11:56.305 --> 01:12:00.430
because the notion of a God
who--

01:12:00.430 --> 01:12:05.948
that Dante is really trying to
save his skin,

01:12:05.948 --> 01:12:11.434
as it were, by claiming a kind
of theological orthodoxy when he

01:12:11.434 --> 01:12:16.564
actually knows that the very
notion of creation whereby God

01:12:16.564 --> 01:12:21.939
opens up into new loves,
it seems to imply that before

01:12:21.939 --> 01:12:27.170
creation God was a lonely guy
looking for a partner,

01:12:27.170 --> 01:12:30.670
some kind of Adam,
Adam in the garden replaces all

01:12:30.670 --> 01:12:31.170
that.
 

01:12:31.170 --> 01:12:32.890
That's really the question.
 

01:12:32.890 --> 01:12:36.403
I think that's a very
interesting idea,

01:12:36.403 --> 01:12:41.671
of course, but I have to--I
will respond not entirely in a

01:12:41.671 --> 01:12:46.479
funny way, but I hope it will
come out as funny.

01:12:46.479 --> 01:12:50.085
It's really the question that
St.

01:12:50.085 --> 01:12:54.930
Augustine asks in the
Confessions.

01:12:54.930 --> 01:12:58.453
There are always those people
who wonder, because that's

01:12:58.453 --> 01:13:01.657
really what the question is,
what did God do before

01:13:01.657 --> 01:13:02.488
creation?
 

01:13:02.488 --> 01:13:02.782
St.
 

01:13:02.782 --> 01:13:07.462
Augustine responds:
he was busy preparing hell to

01:13:07.462 --> 01:13:12.144
people like you who ask these
kinds of questions,

01:13:12.144 --> 01:13:14.680
and think--that's it.
 

01:13:14.680 --> 01:13:21.149
The more seriously idea is that
indeed creation implies,

01:13:21.149 --> 01:13:23.408
I mean that's a response that I
would offer,

01:13:23.408 --> 01:13:29.097
creation implies a beginning
but this creation has been going

01:13:29.097 --> 01:13:34.976
on forever and that the idea of
the Trinitarian God is really a

01:13:34.976 --> 01:13:38.578
response to this problem you
have.

01:13:38.578 --> 01:13:41.399
You obviously are,
I think, it's not obvious but

01:13:41.399 --> 01:13:43.939
you--
to me it's not obvious I think

01:13:43.939 --> 01:13:47.970
that you are appealing to a
different theological paradigm

01:13:47.970 --> 01:13:52.069
of where the unity of God can be
the loneliness of God.

01:13:52.069 --> 01:13:56.962
The Christian reading of that
unity is that there is always a

01:13:56.962 --> 01:14:01.447
productive, an internal life of
love that always goes on

01:14:01.447 --> 01:14:03.158
producing itself.
 

01:14:03.158 --> 01:14:06.844
On that note of theological
grandeur, I thank you and I say

01:14:06.844 --> 01:14:08.560
thank you, we'll see you.
 

01:14:08.560 --> 01:14:09.329
Have a good Thanksgiving.
 

